Sita Lujintanon

Bio

Sita Lujintanon is an epidemiologic-implementation researcher. Her research aims to promote equity in HIV care engagement in Thailand and globally. She has a keen interest in using epidemiologic methods to answer impactful questions with imperfect data and overcoming missing data problems, particularly related to missing outcomes due to loss to follow-up and competing event. She also has a growing interest in applying observational-implementation research approach to rapidly generate evidence to inform effective real-world interventions and policies.

Education

PhD Student in Epidemiolgy | Johns Hopkins School of Public Health | August 2023 - Present

ScM in Epidemiolgy | Johns Hopkins School of Public Health | August 2021 - May 2023

BS in Biological Sciences | Mahidol University International College | September 2016 - July 2019

Experience

Co-Founder & Co-President | Implementation Science Student Working Group | Johns Hopkins School of Public Health | August 2023 - Present

Graduate Research Assistant | Implementation Science Core | LIVE Project | Johns Hopkins School of Public Health | October 2021 - Present

Program Assistant | HIV Treatment Programs | Institute of HIV Research and Innovation | August 2019 - August 2021

Student Intern | Thai Red Cross AIDS Research Centre | August 2017 - August 2019
